IAttribute.description:
Attribute is our nomenclature for 'dimension' as typically used in multi-dimensional BI modeling. The attribute
specifies on what dimension to slice/dice the measures.

In GoodData, each attribute can have multiple different display forms. Display forms essentially provide different
representations for elements in the dimension.

localIdentifier.description:
User-assigned id of the attribute. The value is used to cross-reference model elements that are part
of an execution.

The constraint is that the local identifiers of all measures and attributes in an execution definition MUST
be unique.

displayForm.description:
Reference to display form to use for element representations.

The display form can be referenced by either URL of the display form resource on backend OR by
unique, backend-recognized, identifier of the display form.

Note: specifying display forms by URI is discouraged and WILL be deprecated in the future. The
specification of URL has several drawbacks:

-  Display form URLs are tied to particular analytical workspace; this makes any application that uses
    URL-specified display forms workspace-specific.
-  Display for URLs are not supported by all GoodData backends == this makes any application that uses
    URL-specified display form backend-specific

alias.description:
This is user-assigned alias of the attribute; it is opaque for the backend. When backend returns
metadata about execution results, it WILL include this user-assigned alias in the metadata.

IDimension.description:
Dimensions specify how to organize the results of an execution in a data view. Imagine an attribute in columns vs. rows.
Each dimension requires the itemIdentifiers property, which is an array of items. These items could be attributes' localIdentifiers
or a special 'measureGroup' identifier.

The 'measureGroup' can be used to specify that all measures in the execution definition should be
included in the dimension.

itemIdentifiers.description: List of localIdentifier's of attribute to put in this dimension.

totals.description: List of totals to include in this dimension.

IAttributeSortItem.description:
Sort item which specifies that the result should be sorted by attribute element values in either
ascending or descending order.

attributeIdentifier.description: Local identifier of the attribute to sort by.

aggregation.description: TODO: find out what this does :)

IMeasureSortItem.description:
Sort item which specifies that the result should be sorted by value of a measure. Since the result can have
the value of the measure sliced by one or more attributes, the measure sort item must explicitly specify
the 'slice' by which to sort. This slice is specified by locators.

locators.description: Locators explicitly specifying the exact slice of the measure values to sort by.

IAttributeLocatorItem.description: Locator that specifies a concrete attribute element for which the measure values are sliced.

element.description: Value of the attribute element; TODO: make sure bear is ready for this

IMeasureLocatorItem.description: Locator that specifies a concrete measure to sort by.

IBucket.description:
Bucket is a logical, user-defined grouping of attributes, measures and totals. Buckets can be used to create
a new execution and to derive the result dimensionality. In the context of an existing execution, they serve
as metadata about the execution.

ComputeRatioRule.description: Defines possible compute ratio sanitization rules.

IExecutionDefinition.description:
Execution definition contains 100% complete description of what will the execution compute and how will
the resulting data look like.

IExecutionFactory.description:
Execution factory provides several methods to create a prepared execution from different types
of inputs.

Note: the execution factory WILL perform extensive input validation to ensure that the created
instance of prepared execution is semantically correct.

The contract is that any freshly created instance of {@link IPreparedExecution} MUST be executable (of course
barring desync conditions with the backend where the data model changes).

IPreparedExecution.description:
Prepared execution already knows what data to calculate and allows to specify how the data should be
sorted and shaped into dimensions.

To this end, it provides several functions to customize sort items and dimensions. The prepared execution
is immutable and so all the customization functions WILL result in a new instance of prepared execution.

definition.description: Definition of the execution accumulated to so far.

IExecutionResult.description:
Represents results of execution done with particular definition. Within the result is the description of the
shape of the data and methods to to obtain views on the data.

definition.description: Full definition of execution that yielded this result.

dimensions.description: Description of shape of the data.

IDataView.description: A view on the calculated data.

offset.description: Coordinates of where this data view starts. One coordinate per result dimension.

count.description: Size of data in each dimension.

headerItems.description: TODO: find a way to describe these :)

definition.description: Full definition of execution that computed data included in this DataView.

result.description: Result of the execution that calculated data for this view.

supportsObjectUris.description: Indicates whether the backend is capable to address objects using URIs

canCalculateTotals.description: Indicates whether the backend is capable to calculate and include totals in the resulting data view.

canSortData.description: Indicates whether the backend is capable to sort the result data view.

supportsElementUris.description: Indicates whether the backend can recognize attribute elements by URI.

maxDimensions.description: Indicates maximum result dimensions that the backend is able to produce.

canExportCsv.description: Indicates whether backend can export data to CSV file.

canExportXlsx.description: Indicates whether backend can export data to Excel

canTransformExistingResult.description: Indicates whether backend can transform an existing result into a different shape / sorting / totals.

canExecuteByReference.description: Indicates whether backend can execute an existing, persistent insight by reference.

NotAuthenticated.description:
This exception is thrown when client code triggers an operation which requires authentication but the client
code did not provide credentials or the credentials are invalid.
